Big data analytics

Linear Regression

O.Klopp

Predict personal income from other demographic variables such as age and education from 2011 US Census PUMS data. Will use a small sample of PUMS data available at https://github.com/WinVector/zmPDSwR/blob/master/PUMS/psub.RData

load("psub.RData")  #Note 1
dtrain <- subset(psub,ORIGRANDGROUP >= 500)  #Note 2,3
dtest <- subset(psub,ORIGRANDGROUP < 500)
 #Note 1: Load prepared data frame
#Note 2: The ORGINRANDGROUP column is a random integer from 0 through 999 that was added to the rows during data load to facilitate sampling
#Note 3: Dividing the data into a training set, dtrain, and a test set, dtest

1 Building a linear regression model

For the analysis, well consider the input variables age ( AGEP ), sex (SEX), class of worker (COW), and level of education (SCHL). The output variable is personal income (PINCP).

model <- lm(log(PINCP,base=10) ~ AGEP + SEX + COW + SCHL,data=dtrain)#Note 1,2,3,4
#Note 1: model is the R object to save result in
 #Note 2: PINCP is the dependent variable (in log base 10  scale)
#Note 3: AGEP, SEX, COW, SCHL are the independent variables
#Note 4: dtrain is the data frame to use for training

1.1 Making predictions

Goal: to predict income

dtest$predLogPINCP <- predict(model,newdata=dtest) #Note 1,2,3
dtrain$predLogPINCP <- predict(model,newdata=dtrain) #Note 4
#Note 1: Store the prediction as a new column named predLogPINCP
#Note 2: we use linear regression model
#Note 3: dtest is the Data to use in prediction
#Note 4: Same operation on training data
summary(log(dtrain$PINCP,base=10))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.079   4.400   4.602   4.581   4.778   5.342
summary(predict(model,newdata=dtest))
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   4.182   4.452   4.559   4.569   4.685   5.074

1.3 CHARACTERIZING PREDICTION QUALITY

Plotting the actual y as if it were a function of prediction:

library('ggplot2')
ggplot(data=dtest,aes(x=predLogPINCP,y=log(PINCP,base=10))) +
   geom_point(alpha=0.2,color="black") + #Note 1
   geom_smooth(aes(x=predLogPINCP,#Note 2
      y=log(PINCP,base=10)),color="black") +
   geom_line(aes(x=log(PINCP,base=10), #Note 3
      y=log(PINCP,base=10)),color="blue",linetype=2) +
   scale_x_continuous(limits=c(4,5)) +
   scale_y_continuous(limits=c(3.5,5.5))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 9 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 67 rows containing missing values (geom_path).

#Note 1: creates scatterplot
#Note 2: creates a smooth fit
#Note 3: creates y=x line

Plotting residuals versus the predicted values:

ggplot(data=dtest,aes(x=predLogPINCP,
                     y=predLogPINCP-log(PINCP,base=10))) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.2,color="black") +
  geom_smooth(aes(x=predLogPINCP,
                  y=predLogPINCP-log(PINCP,base=10)),
                  color="black")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess'

1.4 Quantitative summaries of the quality of the predictions and the residuals

Computing R-squered between the prediction and the actual y

rsq <- function(y,f) { 1 - sum((y-f)^2)/sum((y-mean(y))^2) }#Note 1
rsq(log(dtrain$PINCP,base=10),predict(model,newdata=dtrain))#Note 2
## [1] 0.3382568
rsq(log(dtest$PINCP,base=10),predict(model,newdata=dtest))#Note 3
## [1] 0.2605496
#Note 1: define a new function rsq
#Note 2: apply rsq to dtrain
#Note 3: apply rsq to dtest

Computing Residual Standard Error (RSE):

df <- dim(dtrain)[1] - dim(summary(model)$coefficients)[1]#Note 1
rse <- sqrt(sum(residuals(model)^2)/df)
print(rse)
## [1] 0.2690571
# Note1: computing degrees of freedom
